    </div>
</div>


<div class="row">
    <div class="six_part2">
        <img src="~/lib/bootstrap/dist/css/pexels-emmet-128421.jpg" alt="Description of image 1" class="six-part2-image2">
    </div>
    <div class="four_part">
        <h2>The Impact on Climate</h2>
        <p>
            Greenhouse Gas Emissions: The decomposition of organic waste in landfills produces methane. 
            Industries, especially those involved in waste treatment and incineration, release significant amounts of carbon dioxide. 
            These gases trap heat in the Earth's atmosphere, leading to the greenhouse effect and, subsequently, global warming.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>


<div class="row">
    <div class="five_part">
        <h2>Overall Decline in Landfill Emissions: </h2>
        <p>
            One of the most striking features of the graph is the steady decrease in emissions from waste to landfill. 
            Starting at a considerable 17 Mt CO2-e in 1990, the emissions have reduced significantly, 
            reaching 10  Mt CO2-e in 2022 and willing to reaching 6 Mt CO2-e by 2035. 
            This reduction of more than 60% over the 45-year period signifies the country's efforts to minimize landfill waste through policies,
            recycling efforts, waste-to-energy projects, and a general societal shift towards sustainable waste management practices.
        </p>
        <h2>Landfill Remains the Dominant Emitter: </h2>
        <p>
            Despite the commendable reduction in landfill emissions, waste to landfill remains the most significant contributor to waste emissions in 2035.
            This highlights the ongoing challenge of managing and reducing landfill waste, as even with advanced waste treatment technologies and strategies,
            a considerable volume of waste still ends up in landfills.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="five_part">
